      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, my apologies for the goblin metaphor, it was a bit of a whimsical way to express the Monstera's need for attention. Now, focusing on your concern about pests, brown spots on the leaves of your Monstera could indeed be a sign of an infestation. Common culprits include spider mites, mealybugs, and scale insects. These pests can cause discoloration, spots, and even holes in the leaves. To check for these, you can look closely at the underside of the leaves, as well as the stems and soil. If you find any small, white, cotton-like insects, that's likely mealybugs. Tiny, moving dots could be spider mites, and if you see small, hard, shell-like insects, they might be scale. Treating these pests early with a gentle soap and water solution or an insecticidal soap can help keep them at bay. Remember, it's always better to be safe and treat any pests you find, even if they seem insignificant. Your Monstera's health is worth the extra effort!",
